<subSubSection id="FFF02DE5FF8E6023DCC8FB2BB8102E22" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="763" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="B7557E6EFF8E6025DCC8FB2BBF9C2A11" blockId="10.[151,1127,1257,1632]" pageId="10" pageNumber="761">
<emphasis id="859EA27CFF8E6025DCC8FB2BBD6E2A51" bold="true" box="[151,281,1257,1280]" pageId="10" pageNumber="761">Comments.</emphasis>
A rare species, only known from several localities in the eastern part of Nearctic Region (
<bibRefCitation id="D37B039FFF8E6025DCABFACBBD182A71" author="SHAW F. R." box="[244,367,1289,1312]" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" pagination="21 - 31" refId="ref4717" refString="SHAW F. R. 1952: The external anatomy of Palaeoplatyura johnsoni Joh. (Diptera - Mycetophilidae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society 78: 21 - 31." type="journal article" year="1952">SHAW 1952</bibRefCitation>
). This is the first record of this remarkable species from the Palaearctic Region. DNA sequence of the barcode region of COI is also provided (
<tableCitation id="FA684BD5FF8E6025DFD4FAEBBFAA2A11" box="[907,989,1321,1344]" captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="2.[314,361,1165,1184]" captionText="Table 3. List of species included in thisstudy with their Accession numbers." pageId="10" pageNumber="761">Table 3</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B7557E6EFF8E6025DCEAFA8BBE802971" blockId="10.[151,1127,1257,1632]" pageId="10" pageNumber="761">
This species possibly represents one of the most primitive and ancient forms of 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF8E6025DFA6FA8BBCCB2AD1" baseAuthorityName="CHANDLER &amp; PIJNAKKER" baseAuthorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Keroplatidae</taxonomicName>
and can be considered (together with its two extant congeners) as a “living fossil”. Three additional species of 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF8E6025DD27FA4BBE692AF1" authorityName="Meunier" authorityYear="1899" box="[376,542,1417,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Palaeoplatyura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="859EA27CFF8E6025DD27FA4BBE692AF1" box="[376,542,1417,1440]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="761">Palaeoplatyura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were described from the Eocene and Oligocene fossils (
<bibRefCitation id="D37B039FFF8E6025DCC0FA6BBD342A91" author="EVENHUIS N. L." box="[159,323,1449,1472]" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" pagination="1 - 178" refId="ref4269" refString="EVENHUIS N. L. 2006: Catalog of the Keroplatidae of the World (Insecta: Diptera). Bishop Museum Bulletin of Entomology 13: 1 - 178." type="journal article" year="2006">EVENHUIS 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The exact phylogenetic position of this genus is unknown but preliminary data based on the multigene molecular analysis (Mantič et al., in prep.) suggest that the clade containing 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF8E6025DD51FA2BBD1C2951" authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1803" box="[270,363,1513,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Platyura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="859EA27CFF8E6025DD51FA2BBD1C2951" box="[270,363,1513,1536]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="761">Platyura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF8E6025DDC1FA2BBE402951" authorityName="Meunier" authorityYear="1899" box="[414,567,1513,1536]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Paleoplatyura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="859EA27CFF8E6025DDC1FA2BBE402951" box="[414,567,1513,1536]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="761">Paleoplatyura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
branched rather basally, forming a sister group to all the other taxa of 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF8E6025DD13F9CBBDAE2971" baseAuthorityName="CHANDLER &amp; PIJNAKKER" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[332,473,1545,1568]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Keroplatidae</taxonomicName>
, except 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF8E6025DE71F9CBBE832971" box="[558,756,1545,1568]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Arachnocampinae">Arachnocampinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B7557E6EFF8E6023DCEAF9EBB8102E22" blockId="10.[151,1127,1257,1632]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1127,220,371]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="763" pageId="10" pageNumber="761">
This finding also represents a very rare occasion, when a species of 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF8E6025DFDEF9EBB87C2911" baseAuthorityName="CHANDLER &amp; PIJNAKKER" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[897,1035,1577,1600]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="761" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Keroplatidae</taxonomicName>
is found in both the Nearctic and Palaearctic Regions. The only known example in the extant keroplatid fauna is 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF886023DCA9FF1EBE1C2FA2" authority="(Meigen, 1818)" baseAuthorityName="Meigen" baseAuthorityYear="1818" box="[246,619,220,243]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Orfelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="763" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="discoloria">
<emphasis id="859EA27CFF886023DCA9FF1EBDCF2FA2" box="[246,440,220,243]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="763">Orfelia discoloria</emphasis>
(Meigen, 1818)
</taxonomicName>
, but this may change as soon as a detailed revision of that species group is made. There is also a possibility of a recent introduction by human activities as was demonstrated for some other species of 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF886023DF19FEDEBD3E2E02" authority="(CHANDLER &amp; PIJNAKKER 2009)" baseAuthorityName="CHANDLER &amp; PIJNAKKER" baseAuthorityYear="2009" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="763" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Keroplatidae (
<bibRefCitation id="D37B039FFF886023DF80FEDEBD362E02" author="CHANDLER P. J. &amp; PIJNAKKER J." pageId="12" pageNumber="763" pagination="81 - 93" refId="ref4228" refString="CHANDLER P. J. &amp; PIJNAKKER J. 2009: Tropical fungus gnats established in nurseries in the Netherlands (Diptera: Keroplatidae and Mycetophilidae). British Journal of Entomology and Natural History 23: 81 - 93." type="journal article" year="2009">CHANDLER &amp; PIJNAKKER 2009</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Although the 
<typeStatus id="6851C0CCFF886023DDBDFEFEBE672E02" box="[482,528,316,339]" pageId="12" pageNumber="763">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName id="70EA05EDFF886023DED0FEFEBF722E02" authorityName="Johannsen" authorityYear="1910" box="[655,773,316,339]" class="Insecta" family="Keroplatidae" genus="Paleoplatyura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="763" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="johnsoni">
<emphasis id="859EA27CFF886023DED0FEFEBF722E02" box="[655,773,316,339]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="763">P. johnsoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been studied, the identity of the species was established according to the detailed redescription given by 
<bibRefCitation id="D37B039FFF886023DF86FE9EB8142E22" author="SHAW F. R." box="[985,1123,348,371]" pageId="12" pageNumber="763" pagination="21 - 31" refId="ref4717" refString="SHAW F. R. 1952: The external anatomy of Palaeoplatyura johnsoni Joh. (Diptera - Mycetophilidae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society 78: 21 - 31." type="journal article" year="1952">SHAW (1952)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
